Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: CMC Holdings Kenya, Finbank of Nigeria

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-06-27T15:35:43Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-27/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-cmc-holdings-kenya-finbank-of-nigeria.html
The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-
Share Index fell for the first day in four, retreating 0.4
percent to 25,170.63 by the 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according
to an e-mailed statement from the bourse.  Namibia ’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  advanced for the
second day, gaining 0.4 percent to 815.93 by the 4 p.m. close in
Windhoek. Kenya’s All-Share Index snapped three days of
declines, climbing 0.2 percent to 69.93 by the 3 p.m. close in
Nairobi. The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index was little
changed at 1,179 by the 3 p.m. close in Accra. Mauritius’s
SEMDEX Index was little changed at 2,088.08 by the 1:30 p.m.
close in  Port Louis .  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  CMC Holdings Ltd. (CMCH)  , a Kenyan car dealer, rose 15
cents, or 1.4 percent, to 10.8 shillings. Bill Lay, the former
chief executive of General Motors East Africa Ltd., replaced
Martin Forster as Group Managing Director on June 3.  “We have seen a lot of boardroom changes in the last three
months, which means they are getting a new strategy,” George
Bodo, an equity strategist at Nairobi-based Apex Africa, a
brokerage, said in a phone interview today.  Finbank Plc (FIRSTINL)  , a Nigerian lender bailed out by
the central bank in 2009, gained 2 kobo, or 3.6 percent, to 57
kobo, the highest close since June 3, after a court dismissed a
bid to halt the sale of the bank to First City Monument Bank
Plc.  To contact the reporter on this story:
